    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-09-11T16:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-09-11T16:45:00-05:00" n="487"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d487">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.51/1997: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-09-11T16:00:00-05:45">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 11, 1928—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>339. Legation’s 312, August 18, 5 p.m. and Department’s 167, August 22, 2
                        p.m.<note n="79a" xml:id="d487fn79a">Neither printed.</note> President Diaz
                    has informed the Legation in writing that he has ordered the Treasury Department
                    to see that $380,000 from the next surplus is set aside for the exclusive use of
                    the National Guard. He further states that it is his definite intention not to
                    obtain advances against the next surplus for any other purpose.</p>
                <p>The Minister of Finance has given the National Bank irrevocable instructions to
                    give this payment to the <hi rend="italic">guardia</hi> preference over all
                    other payments which may be ordered when the surplus becomes available. The
                    Legation will now seek to obtain Moncada’s promise to abide by this arrangement
                    if he should be elected, and will take up the matter along similar lines with
                        Benard<note n="80" xml:id="d487fn80">Adolfo Benard, Conservative candidate
                        for the Presidency of Nicaragua.</note> after his return unless the
                    Department considers it advisable to discuss it with him in Washington.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
